Cu/NC@SBA-15 catalysts were constructed by pyrolyzing a mixture of Cu(NO3)2 and urea impregnated in SBA-15, and subsequently reducing in hydrogen (Scheme 1
                        ). To modulate the size and distribution of Cu clusters, the ratio of Cu to g-C3N4 was altered by changing the mass ratios of urea to SBA-15, and the Cu/NC@SBA-15−1.0 (1.0 represents the mass ratio of urea to SBA-15) was selected as the most promising sample because of the smallest Cu particle size (Fig. S1b, Supporting Information). Lower g-C3N4 content is insufficient to anchor all Cu particles, leading to local Cu aggregation, while excessive g-C3N4 blocks the pores of SBA-15, resulting in partial Cu precursors nucleating outside the SBA-15 pores. The yield of carbon-nitrogen species that is mainly g-C3N4 is about 4 %. The decreased content in comparison with its counterpart without copper species is due to the successive thermal treatment. The elemental composition of C, N, and H over various samples determined by EA is shown in Table 1
                        .
